        <div class="content-section">
            <h2>Understanding Area Calculation</h2>
            <p>Area is the quantity that expresses the extent of a two-dimensional region, shape, or planar lamina, in the plane. Surface area is its analog on the two-dimensional surface of a three-dimensional object.</p>
            
            <h3>Common Area Formulas</h3>
            
            <h4>Rectangle</h4>
            <p>A rectangle is a quadrilateral with four right angles.</p>
            <div class="formula-box">Area = Length � Width</div>
            
            <h4>Circle</h4>
            <p>A circle is a shape consisting of all points in a plane that are at a given distance from a given point, the centre.</p>
            <div class="formula-box">Area = p � r�</div>
            
            <h4>Triangle</h4>
            <p>A triangle is a polygon with three edges and three vertices.</p>
            <div class="formula-box">Area = � � Base � Height</div>
            
            <h4>Trapezoid</h4>
            <p>A trapezoid is a quadrilateral with at least one pair of parallel sides.</p>
            <div class="formula-box">Area = � � (Base1 + Base2) � Height</div>
            
            <h4>Ellipse</h4>
            <p>An ellipse is a plane curve surrounding two focal points.</p>
            <div class="formula-box">Area = p � a � b</div>
            
            <h3>Applications of Area Calculation</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Construction:</strong> Calculating floor space for carpeting, tiling, or painting walls.</li>
                <li><strong>Land Surveying:</strong> Determining the size of a plot of land.</li>
                <li><strong>Physics:</strong> Calculating pressure (Force/Area) or flux.</li>
                <li><strong>Agriculture:</strong> Estimating crop yields based on field size.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        
